# TypeScript Types

- **Use TypeScript’s type system**: Prefer explicit types for function parameters, return values, and public APIs. Rely on inference where it’s obvious (e.g. `const x = 1`).
- **Avoid `any`**: Do not use `any` unless there is a documented, narrow reason (e.g. typing a truly dynamic third-party API). Use `unknown` and narrow with type guards, or define proper interfaces/types instead.
- **Prefer interfaces or type aliases** for objects and API shapes so they can be reused and checked.
- **Type external data**: When parsing JSON or handling API responses, validate/assert to a known type (e.g. with a schema or type guard) instead of casting to `any`.

## Examples

```typescript
// ❌ BAD — any disables type checking
function handlePayload(data: any) {
  return data.items.map((x: any) => x.id);
}

// ✅ GOOD — explicit types
interface Payload {
  items: { id: string }[];
}
function handlePayload(data: Payload) {
  return data.items.map((x) => x.id);
}
```

```typescript
// ❌ BAD — any on catch
try {
  await fetchUser();
} catch (e: any) {
  console.log(e.message);
}

// ✅ GOOD — unknown + type guard
try {
  await fetchUser();
} catch (e: unknown) {
  const msg = e instanceof Error ? e.message : String(e);
  console.log(msg);
}
```
